# Playbook: gcp-project-bootstrap

> Prepare a GCP project so Terraform can run against it from the devbox:
> billing, Application Default Credentials, required APIs, and the GCS
> bucket that will hold remote Terraform state. Generic template ŌĆö
> replace the `{{PLACEHOLDERS}}`.

## When to use

- You have a Google account with billing enabled and want to host a
  project's infra on GCP.
- Terraform/Ansible will run from the devbox; this is the one-time
  account-side setup that must precede `terraform init`.

If you have no billing account yet, **stop** ŌĆö create it in the Cloud
Console first; this playbook does not create accounts.

## Parameters

| Name | Example | Resolved from |
|---|---|---|
| `{{PROJECT_ID}}` | `toto-mondiale` | operator choice (globally unique) |
| `{{REGION}}` | `us-central1` | free-tier region |
| `{{STATE_BUCKET}}` | `rn-tfstate` | operator choice (globally unique) |
| `{{BILLING_ACCOUNT_ID}}` | `0X0X0X-0X0X0X-0X0X0X` | Cloud Console > Billing |

## Pre-flight checks (do these first, do not skip)

1. `gcloud version` ŌĆö if missing, install the Cloud SDK on the devbox.
2. `gcloud auth list` ŌĆö confirm you are logged in as the owning account.
3. Confirm the billing account ID: `gcloud billing accounts list`.

## Steps

### 1. Create (or select) the project

```bash
gcloud projects create {{PROJECT_ID}} --name="{{PROJECT_ID}}"
gcloud config set project {{PROJECT_ID}}
gcloud billing projects link {{PROJECT_ID}} --billing-account={{BILLING_ACCOUNT_ID}}
```

### 2. Application Default Credentials for Terraform

```bash
gcloud auth application-default login
```

This writes ADC the Terraform google provider picks up automatically.
No service-account key file is created or committed.

### 3. Enable the APIs Terraform will touch

```bash
gcloud services enable \
  compute.googleapis.com \
  iam.googleapis.com \
  logging.googleapis.com \
  cloudbilling.googleapis.com \
  billingbudgets.googleapis.com
```

(`billingbudgets` only if you want the budget alert resource;
`logging` is needed for the `gcplogs` log driver ŌĆö see the `logging`
playbook.)

### 4. Create the GCS bucket for Terraform state

```bash
gcloud storage buckets create gs://{{STATE_BUCKET}} \
  --location={{REGION}} --uniform-bucket-level-access
gcloud storage buckets update gs://{{STATE_BUCKET}} --versioning
```

Then set this bucket in the project's `terraform/backend.tf`
(`bucket = "{{STATE_BUCKET}}"`, `prefix = "<project>/vm"`).

## Verify

- `gcloud config get-value project` returns `{{PROJECT_ID}}`.
- `gcloud services list --enabled | grep compute` is non-empty.
- `gcloud storage buckets describe gs://{{STATE_BUCKET}}` shows
  versioning enabled.
- `gcloud auth application-default print-access-token` returns a token.

## Common pitfalls

- **Bucket name taken**: GCS bucket names are global. Pick a unique
  prefix (initials + `-tfstate`).
- **Budget needs org/billing perms**: `billingbudgets` resources require
  the Billing Account Administrator role. If you lack it, skip the
  budget and set an alert manually in the console.
- **Wrong ADC identity**: `application-default login` is separate from
  `gcloud auth login`. Terraform uses the ADC one.

## What this playbook does NOT do

- Does **not** create the Google account or a billing account.
- Does **not** run Terraform ŌĆö that is `terraform-gce-vm`.
- Does **not** create service-account JSON keys (ADC instead).
